April 30, 2003 
 


 
This paper discusses Skyrmions on the -sphere coupled to
fermions. The resulting Dirac equation commutes with a generalized angular
momentum . For  the Dirac equation can be solved
explicitly for a constant Skyrme configuration and also for a
 symmetric hedgehog configuration. 
We discuss how the spectrum changes due to the presence of a non-trivial 
winding number, and also consider more general Skyrme configurations 
numerically.


 
 pages, 6 figures




Introduction 


The Skyrme model is a classical field theory which describes
atomic nuclei and their low
energy interactions. 
It is a non-linear theory admitting
topological solitons, 
so-called Skyrmions, labelled by a topological charge  which can be 
identified with the baryon number.  
When the theory is quantized the Skyrmions give a
good description of nuclei,  resonance and 
even bound states of nuclei
. 
A striking feature is that Skyrmions can be quantized as fermions 
.  
When the theory is coupled to
a fermion field two different ways of describing fermions appear in
the same theory. Physically, the fermion field can be thought of as light
quarks in the presence of atomic nuclei. 
Hiller calculated the spectrum of
the fermions in the background of a Skyrmion. 
However, the 
approximation for the Skyrmion configuration was very crude. The
spectrum shows a spectral flow of the eigenvalues depending on the
value of the coupling constant. In particular one mode crosses
zero. This general behaviour has been verified by other authors
. 
To gain a better understanding we consider a generalization of the
model.

Since static field configurations in the original Skyrme model 
in flat space are topologically
equivalent to maps , the model can be  generalized to the
base space being a sphere of radius . 
The original model is recovered in the limit
. It turns out that for  and baryon number 
the Faddeev-Bogomolny bound is satisfied and the minimal energy solution can
be worked out explicitly. 
In this case the map  is an isometry. 
For larger  the Skyrmions are localized and tend to the usual 
flat space Skyrmions in the limit . 

Monopoles and Skyrmions have many properties in common, and it is
therefore instructive to recall the results for monopoles. There is an
index theorem making 
use of the Bogomolny equations which states that for  monopoles
there is a  dimensional vector space of fermionic zero modes
. 
Furthermore, the monopole and its fermionic zero mode can be
calculated explicitly for . We will examine how
far we can extend the analogy between monopoles and Skyrmions.

In this paper we study fermions coupled to Skyrmions on . 
The Dirac equation on  is derived in Sect. 
. We also explain the Skyrmion-fermion interaction. 
In Sect. , 
we derive the ordinary differential equation which
describes the solutions with total angular momentum 
for general shape functions. In Sect. , we
give a brief discussion of ordinary differential equations and their regular
singular points.
In Sect. , the equation of Sect. 
 is solved for a constant Skyrme configuration, 
which is equivalent to a mass term for the fermions. 
We also discuss the boundary conditions which are
necessary to derive the spectrum. 
In Sect. , we derive the eigenfunctions and
the spectrum for the hedgehog configuration with the special shape
function . 
In Sect.  the results of Sect.
 and
  are verified numerically. 
The spectrum for more general shape functions is also evaluated 
numerically and compared with results in the literature. 
We find an interesting relationship between the topological charge of 
the Skyrmion and certain singular points. We end with a conclusion.


The Dirac Equation on  

In this section we derive the Dirac equation on a -sphere of radius
. 
First we define an atlas of two charts  and  which
are the stereographic projections from the north pole  and the
south pole , respectively. 
Next we define vierbeins on both charts which uniquely determine a
connection one-form using the metric compatibility condition and the
torsion-free condition. The connection one-form induces the spin
connection so that we can finally write down the Dirac equation for
each chart.(A good discussion of frame fields and
spin-connections can be found in, 
and also in.)  
At the end of this section we discuss the interaction term which
couples fermions and Skyrmions.

