Numerical Results 

In this section we first describe numerical algorithms to calculate
the spectrum for more general shape functions . Then we
discuss the spectrum for the conformal ansatz (). We
also discuss the simple ansatz  which gives rise to
Skyrmions with . Finally, we compare our results with the
literature.

Numerical Algorithm 

The energy spectrum can be calculated for various shape functions
using a standard relaxation method. 
The differential equation () is rewritten as a system of
first order differential equations.

   

The energy  is considered as an additional dependent variable whose
derivative vanishes, , so that the complete system
becomes

  

For simplicity, let us discuss the numerical algorithm for
-symmetric shape function .
Equation () has a regular singular point at  which
implies that at this point we cannot choose value and derivative of
the solution independently. 
However, once the value of  is chosen we can calculate
. In fact, inserting  
into equation () we obtain

 

Similarly we obtain for ,

 

The system () is discretized such that the boundary
conditions at the singular points  are satisfied. 
Starting from an initial configuration the relaxation
algorithm calculates an improved configuration by linearizing the
equation around the solution and minimizing an error function which
indicates how well the discretized equations are satisfied. 

The secret of a successful relaxation method is a good guess for the
starting configuration. Fortunately, for  the analytic solution of
() is known for all possible shape functions
. Therefore, we start with this configuration at  and
increase  by a small amount . The relaxed solution is a
good initial configuration for , and so on.

As a test, the spectrum for  is calculated using the
relaxation method. This reproduces the analytic result.
For  the relaxation method converges well as long as
 is not inside the interval . However, if the
regular singular point  is inside the interval, the
relaxation algorithm no longer converges and has to be modified.
This is one of the main reasons for including the lines  in the 
figures.

In this case a specially chosen shooting method proves more suitable. It 
deals with the additional singularities in  by simply avoiding 
them. 
As mentioned before, our differential equation can be defined on the
complex plane. 
Due to the boundary condition the solution  is an analytic
function. The original solution is recovered by restricting  to be a
real function of a real variable . In order to avoid further
singular points on the real line we can set  where 
. Then equation () induces a differential equation
for , that is the equation is solved on a semi-circular contour. The
resulting differential equation can be written as a system of 5 real first
order differential equations, one of which corresponds to the energy .
Now, the spectrum can be obtained by a standard shooting method,
. The boundary conditions for the shooting
method are that at the singular points  the solution is 
non-singular and furthermore that the equation is real at . Since
the equation has real coefficients, the fact that  is 
real for  implies that  is real for .

A successful shooting method needs a good initial guess. For  we
can rely on our explicit solution and impose  and

 

where equation () follows from equation () and
equation () follows
from the reflection relation for the gamma function (see (6.1.17) in
). As in the relaxation method the initial guess for
the coupling constant  is the value of the solution for
coupling constant .

It is also possible to reconstruct the solution  for 
using the solution  for . Cauchy's
formula states that if  is an analytic function and  is a contour
enclosing the point  then 

 

see for example.
